<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Shadow Minions of Middle-Earth<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=4999'>Nathan "Xavier Six" Cardamone</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=4999&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> January 3, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Well, I hope everyone enjoyed the last installment on the Free Peoples because now its time to get a little shall we say evil. Yes, you love, you hate them, the evil minions of the Shadow. And so it begins.<br>
<br>
Nazgul, the Ringwraiths<br>
<br>
Nazgul, the black riders from Morgul are just about the most cold hearted decks you could ask for of all the shadow races. They are as corrupting as they are evil and have tricks to deal with just about anything thrown at them. <br>
<br>
Good points <br>
<br>
1.	Roaming you say? A Nazgul roaming is a          contradiction in terms. 8 of these guys make their home a site 3 and one actually can never be roaming because Ulaire Nelya is at home at site 2! This is huge because these guys never have to pay that pesky roaming penalty.<br>
2.	Fierce. 7 of the 9 of these guys are fierce or can become fierce by exerting. This essentially means there are two of them! <br>
3.	Powerful. There is no such thing as a weak Nazgul.<br>
4.	Mechanics. Nazgul can seriously tweak the mechanics of the game. From canceling the one ring to adding burdens to converting sites at will. These guys rock.<br>
<br>
Bad Points <br>
<br>
1.	Late game. While the fact that they are never roaming makes the cost of Nazguls about the same as other races early on around site 5 you start feeling the costs. Choke decks hurt a lot too. Morgul Gates came help but you can only pack 4 of them.<br>
2.	Burdensome. Nazgul aret as effective against an opponent who doesnt burden his Frodo and against a guy using sam, this can be a problem.<br>
3.	Unique. Since all the Nazgul are unique, this deck like no other can run into the multiple copy problem. Getting more than one copy of the same Nazgul in hand is common in this deck and can really get annoying.<br>
<br>
Best Bet (In My Opinion) <br>
<br>
Witch King with Pale Blade and Morgul Blade and a Black Steed making him 20-22/fierce/damage +1 OUCH!!!<br>
<br>
Orcs of Moria, denizens of the Deep<br>
<br>
Moria orcs are one of the most popular shadow decks out right now. With low costs and insane numbers these guys are a very strong force. They do however have flaws as well.<br>
<br>
Good points <br>
<br>
1.	Cheap. Moria orcs are the most cost effective of any of the Shadow races. With only four in the Shadow pull it is possible (if not entirely likely) for an Moria deck to throw down unlimited amounts of minions. Your opponent start Legolas and Arwin and using Prancing Pony to pull Aragorn? Well make him hurt at site two by deploying 4 goblin runners and a couple of moria scouts (to eat two archery) and a couple of few scimitars. Frodos in danger now! Thats right for that first site you can throw down all of that, if of course that is in your opening hand. <br>
2.	The Troll. He is big. He is damage +1. He is fierce. His Hammer is cheap and at sites 4 and 5 he deploys for less than the Witch King! This guy is just about one of if not the worst creature in the game and you need moria orcs to play him.<br>
3.	Archery. Orcs have more archers than any other race. With the help of goblin swarm Ive seen the archer total get up to eight and at sight 7 it can be worse!<br>
4.	Versatility. There are more than one way to play moria orcs heck there are more than twenty ways to play. You can center around the troll and go for big fights. You can load up on all the cheap weaker guys and swarm. You can try out archery. You can play dwarf/elf hate. You can try to load up on the goblins 3 types of weapons. The list goes on and on.<br>
<br>
Bad Points <br>
<br>
1.	Weak. Most orcs alone and unarmed are no match for even an unarmed man. Some cant even stack against an elf or dwarf. A few are barely matches for the hobbits! Never send less than 3 or 4 orc against the fellowship it is almost pointless unless they are all armed. <br>
2.	Flimsy. Most orcs have two vitality and many only one. This makes them cannon fodder for archery and wounding fellowship events. Beyond this it is a rare event to see a goblin stay with the fellowship as they move along. They are usually short lived. Always pack goblin armories they can help with this.<br>
3.	Goblins are orcs? Moria orcs are also unfortunately, well orcs. The fellowship packs more orc hate cards than any other hate cards. Glamdring and Sting out at the same time makes play orcs a real pain.<br>
<br>
Best Bet (In My Opinion) <br>
<br>
Trolls Keyward with Goblin Scimitar and Cave Troll of Moria with Hammer: For 9 twilight you get a power ten and a power 18 fierce/damage +2 and with a combined 7 vitality archery shouldnt be a problem.<br>
<br>
<br>
 Isengard Uruk-hai, the Breed of Sarumon<br>
